arch:property.oc:show_val: Phase XI: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
5.50 m north south -by- 1.85 m east west.

Locus 37 is the layer of collapse below Locus 36 in the southwest room. It was a fine, loose brown (Munsell 7.5 YR 4/4) silt, with significant collapse. In addition, there was a significant amount of plaster, along with pottery, bone, metal, and glass. The primarily differentiating feature between Locus 36 and Locus 37 is one of color and composition, and both are part of the collapse of the bath complex (Stage 7).
